node.title: Waukesha police chief says Christmas parade deaths 'not a terrorist event'
node.description: Waukesha's police chief provides an update into the investigation into the incident which left five people dead and dozens injured.
node.content:
["The incident in which an SUV drove through a Christmas parade in the US, leaving five dead and dozens injured, was \"not a terrorist event\", Waukesha's police chief says.", "Chief\u00a0Daniel Thompson said those killed were aged\u00a0from 52 to 81, and 48 people were injured, including two children.", "He said the suspect was not being pursued by police when the SUV ploughed\u00a0through the Wisconsin parade on Sunday local time.", "\"We have information that the suspect, prior to the incident, was involved in a domestic disturbance,\" Chief Thompson said.", "He identified the person in custody as Darrell E\u00a0Brooks, 39.", "Court records showed Mr Brooks was on bail for unrelated matters after posting a $US1,000 ($1,383)\u00a0bond earlier this\u00a0 month.", "The Milwaukee County District Attorney's office released a statement on Monday detailing the pending charges against Mr Brooks and said it was conducting an internal review of the decision involving Mr Brook's bail recommendation.", "\"The state's bail recommendation in this case was inappropriately low in light of the nature of the recent charges and the pending charges against Mr\u00a0Brooks,\" read the statement, which made no reference of the parade incident.", "", "
NBC reporter Elise Romas and CBS reporter Adam Rife describe the scene in Wisconsin.
", "On the morning after Sunday's carnage, a pink hat, a lone shoe and lollies lay strewn across the main thoroughfare in\u00a0Waukesha, roughly 32km\u00a0west of Milwaukee.\u00a0", "Dozens of orange evidence circles were painted on the street and most shops were closed in the city's downtown district.", "A woman tied a bouquet of flowers to a street post as police officers blocked intersections along the main road.", "The FBI is assisting local police with their investigation.", "More to come.", "Reuters"]
